Citations
Date: 0/0/1899
Source: Personal Communication
Author: P.S. ARDERN
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote: I don't remember hearing <i>cronk</i> after my schooldays (which ended in 1899), nor with any other sense than `ill'. I suggest a derivation from a Yiddish pronunciation of Ger <i>krank</i> [as does Morris].
Notes:  (Auckland)

Date: 17/3/1906
Source: NZ Truth
Author:
Vol / Page: 39/3/4
Edition:
Quote: Eventually he took ill and died ... and before his death he was in a very cronk state, being practically [comatose].
Notes: [Christchurch corresp.]

Date: 7/10/1933
Source: Press, The
Author:
Vol / Page: 15
Edition:
Quote: <i>Cronk</i>: Ill, not at all well.
Notes: (Acland Gloss.)

Date: 0/0/1929
Source: Whitcombe's Etym. Dict. Aust-NZ Suppl.
Author:
Vol / Page: 3
Edition:
Quote: <i>cronk a.</i> cranky; unsteady; of race-horses, unfit to run;-sl. dishonestly obtained. [Ger. krank, sick, ill]
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1941
Source: NZ Slang
Author: BAKER
Vol / Page: 62
Edition:
Quote: <i>Cronk</i>, sick, worthless, or illegal.
Notes: [Australian borrowings]

Date: 0/0/1968
Source: NZ Contemp. Dict. Suppl. (Collins)
Author:
Vol / Page: 6
Edition:
Quote: <i>cronk adj. (Sl.</i>) ill, unwell, worthless, out of order, originally applied to dishonest horse-racing or prize-fighting <i>v.t. cronk up</i>, fail in health.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1988
Source: Dictionary of Kiwi Slang, A
Author: McGILL
Vol / Page: 32
Edition:
Quote: <i>cronk</i> ill; originally among shearers; since 1880s of a horse made to appear ill to cheat its backers; from German `krank', ill. NZA.
Notes:
